1
00:00:00,980 --> 00:00:03,280
Hi everyone, welcome to my channel.

2
00:00:04,520 --> 00:00:10,320
Today we have a very interesting topic on the lab power supply.

3
00:00:11,120 --> 00:00:15,440
Namely, we'll pick and tune the current protection.

4
00:00:16,220 --> 00:00:23,100
A very important parameter that defines the whole idea of this device.

5
00:00:24,020 --> 00:00:32,480
This is the moment when the device will hold a certain current passing through the power switches.

6
00:00:33,700 --> 00:00:40,980
With this we'll regulate the output parameters and adjust under load.

7
00:00:42,460 --> 00:00:51,500
Here in front of you is the schematic diagram, which for today looks like this.

8
00:00:51,800 --> 00:01:03,640
It'll still get filled out, with some modifications, but the elements presented here won't be subject to changes.

9
00:01:04,140 --> 00:01:09,240
So, let me dwell on the current protection in more detail.

10
00:01:09,640 --> 00:01:15,080
I brought it to pin 9 of the UC3825N chip.

11
00:01:16,780 --> 00:01:37,040
An interesting property of this chip is that when voltage of 0.9 V is applied, the current protection trip starts — that is, the duration of output pulses reduces.

12
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:45,920
And this parameter, from 0.9 V to 1.3 V, sustains the width reduction.

13
00:01:46,380 --> 00:01:57,320
When the voltage amplitude reaches 1.3 V, generation of control pulses fully stops at the output.

14
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:00,600
That is, a small window of possibilities.

15
00:02:01,140 --> 00:02:08,360
To fit into it, we need to do the wiring of this system and a sensitive current sensor.

16
00:02:09,060 --> 00:02:19,380
The current sensor — this is schematically shown on the drawing — is a ring with wire wound around it as a spiral.

17
00:02:20,360 --> 00:02:27,320
Physically it's this ring, its dimensions are also shown on the drawing.

18
00:02:28,360 --> 00:02:33,800
I'm making it on Epcos ferrite, with permeability 2200.

19
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:45,100
If you use other ferrites, then accordingly the data I'll cite in this video will be slightly different for you.

20
00:02:45,580 --> 00:02:48,380
In practice everyone will need to pick this.

21
00:02:49,500 --> 00:03:11,520
Experimentally I found that for my ferrite, this core, for proper sensitivity — so I could regulate from 0.5 A up to the point I want, and for me this will be 20 A consumption from a 12 V battery —

22
00:03:12,520 --> 00:03:21,080
I needed to wind 120 turns of 0.35 mm wire on this core.

23
00:03:21,900 --> 00:03:37,760
I tried experiments on the same cores with other wire diameters, in particular 0.45, but that turn count turned out too small.

24
00:03:38,060 --> 00:03:48,980
Here you'd have to wind in several layers, so I went experimentally toward reducing the wire gauge and stopped at the optimal mode.

25
00:03:49,120 --> 00:03:56,980
That is, this core is wound fully around the circumference in one layer.

26
00:03:57,160 --> 00:04:10,340
Before starting work on winding wire on this core, it won't be superfluous to calculate the total wire length that'll fit on this magnetic core.

27
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:26,080
For this I use the known formula for circumference length expressed through diameter, where P is the circumference length, π is the constant 3.14, and D is the diameter.

28
00:04:26,940 --> 00:04:32,860
Measure this diameter with calipers and substitute it into the formula.

29
00:04:33,360 --> 00:04:39,100
Multiply and get a circumference length of 42.39 mm.

30
00:04:39,900 --> 00:04:45,240
Next we need to decide on the wire diameter we'll wind with.

31
00:04:45,300 --> 00:04:48,060
In my case this is 0.35 mm.

32
00:04:48,820 --> 00:04:50,200
Then proceed like this.

33
00:04:50,860 --> 00:04:55,640
Divide the circumference length by the wire diameter and get the turn count.

34
00:04:55,980 --> 00:05:00,760
121 turns will fit on this core.

35
00:05:01,180 --> 00:05:04,140
Now we should know the length of one turn.

36
00:05:04,240 --> 00:05:08,320
For this, tightly wrap the core with wire, straighten it out, and measure it.

37
00:05:08,860 --> 00:05:12,400
In this case the turn length came out to 21 mm.

38
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:22,160
Now multiply the turn count by the length of one turn and get the wire length in millimeters.

39
00:05:22,700 --> 00:05:30,980
Then divide by 1000 mm per meter and express the length now in meters.

40
00:05:31,160 --> 00:05:35,060
In my case it came to 2.54 m.

41
00:05:35,820 --> 00:05:39,380
Approximately with leads I took 2.6 m.

42
00:05:40,180 --> 00:05:48,000
I wound it with the help of a bobbin like this, from copper wire with flattened edges.

43
00:05:50,080 --> 00:05:56,960
This is the product I got in the course of doing the work.

44
00:05:57,080 --> 00:06:00,180
It took about an hour of continuous work.

45
00:06:01,640 --> 00:06:05,880
Now you can see I brought out its leads.

46
00:06:06,280 --> 00:06:16,280
The start lead is soldered directly to the start of the wire, and the end lead is in heat shrink.

47
00:06:16,860 --> 00:06:21,540
Now this part should be well insulated.

48
00:06:21,960 --> 00:06:38,520
I'll insulate it with the help of masking tape, to protect the wire with which the current-pickup transformer is wound from mechanical damage.

49
00:06:39,360 --> 00:06:46,440
I finished the insulation protection of the current sensor and while the glue dries, fixing the tape end.

50
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:48,980
Let me explain a bit using the schematic.

51
00:06:49,880 --> 00:06:58,240
On the schematic you can notice graphic notations at various points.

52
00:06:58,820 --> 00:07:03,000
This is nothing other than a terminal block.

53
00:07:04,060 --> 00:07:09,680
At the boundary of these parts wire connections happen.

54
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:18,840
These are sold, cost not much — 40 rubles a piece with the mating part.

55
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:26,600
It connects like this and is very convenient, you can cut off any number of contact blocks.

56
00:07:29,700 --> 00:07:33,140
This is how the board looks in finished form.

57
00:07:34,840 --> 00:07:37,420
This is the back side of the board.

58
00:07:38,440 --> 00:07:40,900
Wiring done by point-to-point mount.

59
00:07:42,920 --> 00:07:46,120
Nothing super-complex.

60
00:07:47,280 --> 00:07:55,720
Also on the schematic there are leads 1, 2 — I explained these in the previous video.

61
00:07:56,560 --> 00:07:58,740
And letter notations.

62
00:07:59,380 --> 00:08:02,880
Wires will also be connected to these letter notations.

63
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:08,140
I did it so there wouldn't be a pile-up of connectors.

64
00:08:08,480 --> 00:08:11,140
That is, they'll be on another sheet.

65
00:08:11,560 --> 00:08:16,240
The second part of the schematic, this is sheet 1, passes to sheet 2.

66
00:08:17,160 --> 00:08:22,360
And there contacts will be connected with the corresponding letters.

67
00:08:23,480 --> 00:08:29,200
These contacts at us are under designations E, F.

68
00:08:29,320 --> 00:08:36,840
This is for switching the PWM controller to standby mode.

69
00:08:37,540 --> 00:08:49,020
That is, when voltage is applied here — I used current output — at pin 9 of the chip it stops generating control pulses.

70
00:08:49,500 --> 00:08:56,280
You can notice that here the letter F and the F output are assembled on a divider from resistors.

71
00:08:56,400 --> 00:09:01,920
Here I approximately picked the divider so it'd be 2-2.5 volts.

72
00:09:02,480 --> 00:09:10,020
From this point, here actually is located the switch and button that we close.

73
00:09:10,580 --> 00:09:15,520
And when voltage potential is applied here, generation stops.

74
00:09:15,640 --> 00:09:22,880
As soon as voltage potential from here is turned off, the chip switches back to operating mode.

75
00:09:23,080 --> 00:09:25,860
Which will be quite convenient in practice.

76
00:09:26,660 --> 00:09:36,480
Also with letters C and D are marked the inputs for the PC817 opto-coupler.

77
00:09:37,020 --> 00:09:42,340
Here voltage feedback will also be connected.

78
00:09:43,160 --> 00:09:51,860
Anyone who finds it convenient can make voltage regulation feedback if they slightly change this scheme.

79
00:09:52,480 --> 00:10:03,680
But I'll use this for stopping generation when 1000 volts is reached at the power supply output.

80
00:10:05,060 --> 00:10:12,780
The voltage control at me is assembled on this chain of resistances.

81
00:10:13,040 --> 00:10:21,700
Variable resistance of 2 kOhm and limiting resistances of 1 kOhm and 2.4 kOhm.

82
00:10:25,780 --> 00:10:34,120
Leads marked A and B — exactly here power will be supplied to the bridge from the switches.

83
00:10:36,320 --> 00:10:51,560
Now I've already partly assembled the system, attached the power module, power pulse transformer to its regular place, cleaned up and soldered the leads.

84
00:10:53,420 --> 00:10:57,100
Now we'll move on to fastening the current sensor.

85
00:10:57,680 --> 00:11:00,640
You can see.

86
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:17,380
It's visible the wire is bent in such a way, going from this primary winding, that it forms a bend at 90 degrees and goes to the transistors.

87
00:11:17,380 --> 00:11:24,320
That is, at this point we can hook in.

88
00:11:24,460 --> 00:11:27,140
This goes further to the primary winding.

89
00:11:27,700 --> 00:11:32,460
And at this point the current sensor will be placed.

90
00:11:32,860 --> 00:11:38,860
Now I'll mount, solder, and move on to installing the board in its regular place.

91
00:11:39,780 --> 00:11:42,620
The current sensor is installed in its regular place.

92
00:11:43,300 --> 00:11:44,880
Here it is on the wire.

93
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:48,260
The board is also installed.

94
00:11:49,780 --> 00:11:50,860
Everything connected.

95
00:11:51,020 --> 00:12:06,340
Now for the next experiment, which consists of determining at what frequency our converter will work in steady mode, we need a load — in this case a 60 W 220 V lamp,

96
00:12:06,340 --> 00:12:21,640
a diode bridge with a capacitor, to look at the DC voltage on this lamp, a voltmeter — in this case a tester that'll track the voltage on the lamp — a power source,

97
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:32,500
a battery, and an ammeter that'll show the consumption of the whole device from the battery.

98
00:12:34,160 --> 00:12:48,020
To start, we disconnect the current sensor, break one of the wires — it doesn't matter which — in this case I unsoldered it from the board,

99
00:12:53,140 --> 00:13:13,620
this wire, and we should connect these two wires together in the scheme — that is, connect pin 9 of the chip to ground. These two wires I connect, in this case they go out connected

100
00:13:13,620 --> 00:13:15,100
to the board.

101
00:13:16,720 --> 00:13:34,960
Next step is to switch the trim resistance on the scheme — this 10 kOhm resistor — to the extreme position, so that the frequency of pulses controlling the FET transistor gates would be

102
00:13:34,960 --> 00:13:38,940
maximum — in this case 190 kHz.

103
00:13:40,680 --> 00:13:57,600
The course of work will go like this: track the consumption and track the voltage on the lamp, and when we find the moment at which the voltage on the lamp is maximum and the consumption is

104
00:13:57,600 --> 00:13:59,160
minimum, we stop adjusting.

105
00:13:59,200 --> 00:14:12,800
The chain is assembled, now we should switch this resistance responsible for pulse duration into the position where the duration of control pulses on the switches will be maximum.

106
00:14:13,620 --> 00:14:30,780
I did this beforehand — this variable resistance — now I apply power to the DC-DC converter and see that the load lit up with some glow, and the voltage is slowly

107
00:14:30,780 --> 00:14:31,640
growing on it.

108
00:14:31,820 --> 00:14:39,000
This growth will last some time because right now the transformer isn't in its mode, the frequency is high.

109
00:14:39,920 --> 00:14:47,340
And now observe the ammeter readings at the input and the voltage on the load.

110
00:14:48,240 --> 00:14:52,000
We need to set the maximum voltage on the load.

111
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:17,120
Now I'll slowly drop the frequency, and here the frequency went down, and we see that the voltage at us had a moment when it jumped to 200 volts, but the consumption is around 5 amps.

112
00:15:18,580 --> 00:15:27,920
I'm looking for the point where consumption will drop — here the ammeter needle is slowly moving to the left.

113
00:15:36,930 --> 00:15:39,070
Here I reached a stable moment.

114
00:15:39,550 --> 00:15:47,410
Consumption stopped at 4.5 amps, and the voltage is around 185 volts.

115
00:15:47,470 --> 00:15:49,090
Now let's see if there's a lower one.

116
00:15:51,070 --> 00:15:55,150
There's a moment where it jumps for us.

117
00:15:56,570 --> 00:16:01,370
Raise a bit, consumption drops and output drops.

118
00:16:02,810 --> 00:16:17,490
Reduce a bit more, and here there's a moment, narrow, where minimum consumption is less than 4.5 amps and voltage is around 180 volts.

119
00:16:19,510 --> 00:16:24,690
That's one point, now let's see if there's another with reducing frequency.

120
00:16:28,310 --> 00:16:32,690
Here was a good mode — 190 volts.

121
00:16:33,490 --> 00:16:37,020
Now go lower.

122
00:16:40,120 --> 00:16:42,020
Here will be the second point.

123
00:16:43,260 --> 00:16:54,840
Pay attention — 190 volts and consumption less than 4.5 amps, somewhere around 4.2 amps.

124
00:16:55,460 --> 00:16:58,480
This will most likely be our operating point.

125
00:16:58,620 --> 00:17:10,300
But I did such tests beforehand, and for this core with three layers, this frequency is 55 kHz.

126
00:17:10,640 --> 00:17:14,020
Frequency we can already look at with the help of an oscilloscope.

127
00:17:14,980 --> 00:17:17,580
I'll hook up the device and we'll see this.

128
00:17:17,620 --> 00:17:18,460
Now look.

129
00:17:18,960 --> 00:17:26,960
I'll go down further, observing the operating mode.

130
00:17:27,270 --> 00:17:28,160
Going down,

131
00:17:33,600 --> 00:17:38,200
and we see the voltage starts to sag,

132
00:17:43,780 --> 00:17:47,180
consumption stays the same.

133
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:51,700
Going lower in frequency makes no sense already.

134
00:17:51,800 --> 00:17:56,800
I'll return to the original position where there'll be maximum voltage.

135
00:18:08,170 --> 00:18:09,690
Here it's 185.

136
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:23,520
Skipped a bit.

137
00:18:25,480 --> 00:18:30,180
Here it is, this is the operating point.

138
00:18:30,260 --> 00:18:33,980
And now let's measure it with the oscilloscope.

139
00:18:35,600 --> 00:18:40,620
I hooked up the oscilloscope and we can observe the oscillogram.

140
00:18:44,380 --> 00:18:50,140
In this case I stopped at a frequency of 50 kHz.

141
00:18:50,940 --> 00:18:56,160
This is the working range of the core — somewhere 45-60 kHz.

142
00:18:56,300 --> 00:19:03,420
On average I'll stop at 55 kHz of system operation.

143
00:19:04,220 --> 00:19:09,480
This will be the normal zone for the core to work in.

144
00:19:11,040 --> 00:19:13,740
Raise the frequency slightly.

145
00:19:22,460 --> 00:19:36,940
At this frequency, look now, consumption makes 4.2 A and 180 V on the load.

146
00:19:40,880 --> 00:19:47,360
On a 12 V battery — got jolted by the current a bit.

147
00:19:47,780 --> 00:19:53,940
It happens — the hot end uninsulated bites you.

148
00:20:01,190 --> 00:20:03,750
Here we have voltage regulation present.

149
00:20:08,220 --> 00:20:12,580
With this, the frequency adjustment ends.

150
00:20:12,780 --> 00:20:18,600
Now we'll move on to tuning the current feedback.

151
00:20:18,940 --> 00:20:23,600
For the next stage of tuning we definitely need the oscilloscope.

152
00:20:23,720 --> 00:20:31,100
With it we'll track whether the current protection is working or not, and how correctly it works.

153
00:20:31,900 --> 00:20:43,500
The probes in this case — two channels will be used — I connected at these points that send the control signal to the drivers, point 1 and 2.

154
00:20:45,180 --> 00:20:51,540
I start the system without applying power to the power module.

155
00:20:53,180 --> 00:20:59,580
We see the oscillogram of the system's work.

156
00:21:00,360 --> 00:21:14,120
And now I'll reduce the working duration to a position slightly less than half.

157
00:21:14,580 --> 00:21:22,880
Next we need a hefty load with small ohmic resistance — for example a 300 W lamp.

158
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:25,260
And now what we'll do.

159
00:21:26,280 --> 00:21:37,640
Tracking the desired consumption current at which we'd want to stop on the ammeter, I bring the ammeter reading slightly above that point.

160
00:21:37,780 --> 00:21:45,660
In this case I calculate that I'll have maximum consumption of 20 A, maybe slightly higher.

161
00:21:46,340 --> 00:21:57,640
For a 12 V battery this is already a hefty consumption, and going higher than that makes no sense — otherwise the battery will discharge very fast.

162
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:00,720
For my needs this is plenty.

163
00:22:01,480 --> 00:22:04,260
The load we'll turn on between these leads.

164
00:22:04,560 --> 00:22:12,240
First lead of the transformer and last, to give maximum load that can be.

165
00:22:13,080 --> 00:22:18,580
Here is the duration now, and I'll briefly connect the lamp.

166
00:22:19,920 --> 00:22:20,780
Ah, power.

167
00:22:20,960 --> 00:22:24,740
Power can now be applied to the power module.

168
00:22:24,900 --> 00:22:25,900
Apply power.

169
00:22:27,300 --> 00:22:29,360
And now turn on.

170
00:22:30,700 --> 00:22:32,500
Yes, power applied.

171
00:22:35,160 --> 00:22:40,460
We see on the ammeter 11 A consumption.

172
00:22:41,640 --> 00:22:44,160
There's a discharge.

173
00:22:44,860 --> 00:22:48,760
Add the duration of control pulses a bit.

174
00:22:55,520 --> 00:22:56,920
14.

175
00:23:00,200 --> 00:23:01,780
Add more.

176
00:23:06,790 --> 00:23:07,630
19.

177
00:23:12,090 --> 00:23:12,890
More.

178
00:23:21,620 --> 00:23:25,140
Already flies past 30, a lot.

179
00:23:27,080 --> 00:23:33,220
The converter can of course work in this mode and more, but for that it'd need cooling air.

180
00:23:34,100 --> 00:23:37,320
I wanted the system to work specifically without cooling.

181
00:23:39,020 --> 00:23:41,120
21 A at maximum.

182
00:23:41,900 --> 00:23:43,480
Approximately what's needed.

183
00:23:44,500 --> 00:23:53,300
Now, when it's tuned like this, we can open these contacts.

184
00:23:53,640 --> 00:23:56,660
Right now they're closed.

185
00:23:57,060 --> 00:24:00,780
And here we'll pick a resistance.

186
00:24:01,240 --> 00:24:05,080
It connects at this point.

187
00:24:05,140 --> 00:24:11,460
And this resistance, it's marked, determines the final trip current of the current protection.

188
00:24:12,460 --> 00:24:18,340
That is, we need to tune this protection slightly above 20 A.

189
00:24:20,660 --> 00:24:27,580
Now I start picking the resistance starting from approximately 10 Ohm.

190
00:24:27,800 --> 00:24:35,240
Solder 10 Ohm and look at what amperage of consumption the current protection trips at.

191
00:24:36,220 --> 00:24:38,580
So, I soldered a 10 Ohm resistor.

192
00:24:38,740 --> 00:24:42,880
I recommend you solder properly so the contact is very good.

193
00:24:43,500 --> 00:24:47,540
And now short the transformer output.

194
00:24:48,960 --> 00:24:52,640
We see, observe the changes in duration.

195
00:24:53,480 --> 00:24:59,660
The duration of control pulses, when load is connected, it reduces.

196
00:24:59,820 --> 00:25:06,740
That is, the system starts confidently catching and the current protection trips.

197
00:25:06,900 --> 00:25:16,100
Now I can add maximum duration of the control signal and test the current protection.

198
00:25:17,780 --> 00:25:20,620
Here we see 10 A.

199
00:25:21,060 --> 00:25:23,960
Pay attention to the ammeter.

200
00:25:26,980 --> 00:25:29,100
Now check on a short.

201
00:25:30,320 --> 00:25:32,960
On a short, slightly above 10 A.

202
00:25:33,940 --> 00:25:42,980
The protection's already working — we can confidently say the turn count of the transformer was picked correctly.

203
00:25:45,880 --> 00:25:53,860
Now the task is to bring the consumption at current protection trip up to 20 A.

204
00:25:54,380 --> 00:25:58,280
For this — this resistance that I soldered —

205
00:25:58,640 --> 00:26:07,100
we'll smoothly reduce its rating in Ohms until we bring it to this point.

206
00:26:07,780 --> 00:26:13,520
The duration of control pulses meanwhile can be held at maximum.

207
00:26:13,920 --> 00:26:17,580
Next test for us — 8.5 Ohm.

208
00:26:18,840 --> 00:26:20,080
Apply power.

209
00:26:21,220 --> 00:26:26,660
We see the duration of pulses at maximum and the load.

210
00:26:27,500 --> 00:26:29,860
Observe the ammeter.

211
00:26:31,620 --> 00:26:33,440
11.5 A.

212
00:26:35,360 --> 00:26:45,280
Don't pay attention to the fact that the 300 W lamp is glowing weakly, because this is the last lead, it's high-voltage.

213
00:26:45,460 --> 00:26:49,180
You see for yourselves what voltage stretches here.

214
00:26:50,400 --> 00:26:55,100
The lamp will burn normally on a reduced number of taps.

215
00:26:58,980 --> 00:27:01,680
Short — 11.5 A.

216
00:27:01,920 --> 00:27:04,440
We can reduce the resistance rating further.

217
00:27:05,560 --> 00:27:09,240
Next resistance — 4.6 Ohm.

218
00:27:10,420 --> 00:27:15,200
Apply power and test on load.

219
00:27:17,920 --> 00:27:21,140
18 A is the trip point.

220
00:27:22,780 --> 00:27:29,900
As you can see on this high-voltage tap, the lamp glow increases.

221
00:27:31,560 --> 00:27:35,360
Now I test through the lamp, do a short circuit.

222
00:27:36,460 --> 00:27:39,100
Same 18 A on the case.

223
00:27:42,200 --> 00:27:50,040
We're somewhere close, and now we need to reduce by 0.1 Ohm.

224
00:27:50,860 --> 00:27:51,980
I'll do this.

225
00:27:51,980 --> 00:27:58,820
So as not to drag out the video, I won't show the whole picking system by 0.1 Ohm.

226
00:27:59,700 --> 00:28:04,100
I picked it like this — now visible what a garland of resistances.

227
00:28:05,040 --> 00:28:09,100
Its total resistance is 4.1 Ohm.

228
00:28:11,060 --> 00:28:14,680
Now I achieved what I need.

229
00:28:15,280 --> 00:28:21,080
Apply power and on load.

230
00:28:22,500 --> 00:28:23,860
20 A.

231
00:28:25,060 --> 00:28:27,460
And check on short.

232
00:28:28,820 --> 00:28:31,100
Short also 20 A.

233
00:28:31,740 --> 00:28:40,020
On the oscilloscope it's also well visible that the current protection trips, reduces the duration of control pulses.

234
00:28:40,740 --> 00:28:41,540
All excellent.

235
00:28:43,300 --> 00:28:54,660
I want to say that such an operating mode when a short circuit happens — this is the most complex mode for switch operation, in such a current-limiting mode.

236
00:28:56,020 --> 00:29:01,840
And in this mode the heat sink will heat up the most.

237
00:29:04,070 --> 00:29:20,520
If, for example, you operate in such a mode, manually reduce, then here heating will be, here I set it, and in such a mode heating will be minimum.

238
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:31,240
And in the mode when the duration is at maximum — specifically when the system trips the current protection — at that moment heating of the heat sink will be exactly here.

239
00:29:31,360 --> 00:29:33,040
But the heating shouldn't be strong.

240
00:29:34,300 --> 00:29:42,720
Approximately at... now I'll short the system, look.

241
00:29:43,600 --> 00:29:45,840
The battery is already draining of course.

242
00:29:49,760 --> 00:29:50,740
Look.

243
00:29:51,960 --> 00:29:57,440
There's heat release, on the order of 50 degrees.

244
00:29:58,600 --> 00:30:06,000
This converter isn't planned to operate in such a tough mode, especially without cooling.

245
00:30:06,800 --> 00:30:09,080
So everything's normal.

246
00:30:09,900 --> 00:30:18,500
The next stage is that we need to tune the current protection trip.

247
00:30:18,660 --> 00:30:22,620
We conducted the experiment, picked this resistance here.

248
00:30:23,520 --> 00:30:34,920
To this we'll add a variable resistance, so we'd have smooth trip regulation from 0.10 A to 20 A.

249
00:30:35,200 --> 00:30:37,260
Any regulation can be set.

250
00:30:37,260 --> 00:30:44,680
I decided to stop on this circuit solution for current protection regulation.

251
00:30:45,380 --> 00:30:50,380
It's done on two resistances connected in series.

252
00:30:51,460 --> 00:30:56,600
And in parallel to one of them is connected a variable resistance.

253
00:30:57,400 --> 00:31:07,220
Thus, in case the slider middle point fails, we have current protection that with the help of these two resistances remains functional.

254
00:31:07,440 --> 00:31:19,340
And we don't risk getting into such a situation when, with wear, if we simply connected this point here, at some moment our system would be left without current protection.

255
00:31:19,400 --> 00:31:29,740
If you remove this resistance, then the system will operate in the mode of the smallest current passing through the power switches.

256
00:31:30,100 --> 00:31:32,960
It'll supply the smallest duration on their opening.

257
00:31:34,200 --> 00:31:35,920
Now I'll show how this works.

258
00:31:36,660 --> 00:31:38,360
Approximately picked ratings.

259
00:31:38,640 --> 00:31:40,320
Further they'll be slightly changed.

260
00:31:41,120 --> 00:31:41,940
Announcing.

261
00:31:41,980 --> 00:31:47,240
0.7 Ohm, 120 Ohm, and 1 kOhm — this resistance.

262
00:31:48,100 --> 00:31:49,300
Apply power.

263
00:31:52,200 --> 00:32:01,580
Regulation starts from 1 Amp and goes up to 19 Amps.

264
00:32:02,220 --> 00:32:03,900
Add with the slider.

265
00:32:08,460 --> 00:32:10,520
Slowly moving.

266
00:32:11,400 --> 00:32:15,500
See how the current protection works now.

267
00:32:16,880 --> 00:32:24,300
Tune for example to 2 Amps consumption.

268
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:29,740
Further — 5 Amps consumption.

269
00:32:30,320 --> 00:32:34,340
See the duration of control pulses.

270
00:32:38,910 --> 00:32:47,310
And it doesn't matter anymore how we control the output voltage — we can only reduce it.

271
00:32:47,590 --> 00:32:54,750
But on increase to maximum, we'll have our desired one tuned with this slider.

272
00:32:55,650 --> 00:32:59,790
Looks like the resistance turned out a bit low-quality.

273
00:32:59,950 --> 00:33:01,610
There are sharp jerks.

274
00:33:02,130 --> 00:33:03,310
Will need to replace.

275
00:33:03,990 --> 00:33:05,310
But this is all fixable.

276
00:33:05,530 --> 00:33:06,910
Now bring to maximum.

277
00:33:08,330 --> 00:33:09,830
18 Amps.

278
00:33:11,470 --> 00:33:15,410
Yes, the resistance needs to be changed, but regulation is present.

279
00:33:18,730 --> 00:33:21,870
So on this scheme we can stop.

280
00:33:24,930 --> 00:33:32,110
At this point we can consider tuning of the current protection finished.

281
00:33:33,110 --> 00:33:37,330
The system successfully handles via feedback.

282
00:33:38,490 --> 00:33:39,710
Until the next videos.

283
00:33:39,970 --> 00:33:43,250
Successful experiments to everyone, and all the best.
